Harbor Seals [ds_106]

Data Courtesy of data.gov.

The website that stores the data is https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/harbor-seals-ds106-9df81

Link to Dataset: https://data-cdfw.opendata.arcgis.com/api/download/v1/items/532cb5969c3c4a50abf57c7d2656306f/csv?layers=0

This dataset was collected by the California Department of Fish and Game (CDFG)

Size: 228 KB

According to Data.gov, "this dataset is intended for public use and access"

The data table includes information obtained by the California Department of Fish and Game (CDFG) during their 2001-2003 aerial photographic surveys of the harbor seal’s population living in California. This study examined the number of harbor seals present at various locations and compared their numbers to previous studies.

Data includes specific locations (County, Islands, Offshore/Onshore, X/Y Coordinates, Latitude and Longitude), Substrates (Where the harbor seals hauled out of the ocean to rest and/or give birth), Time and Date of the Photograph, The amount of photographs taken at specific locations, Estimate of the Population, Total count of the population, and the current flight number that captured the photo. Possible complications include columns H and I (Aerial Estimate and Grand Count, respectively), and column K (Time and Date) during the 2001 survey.

Name of the Dataset: Harbor_Seals_[ds106].csv

Tutorial 1: Hypothesis Testing¶

Introduction:¶

Our world relies on data more than any other time in history. From medicine and healthcare, quality control and manufacturing, economics, finance and market research (just to name a few), Government agencies, educational institutions and private businesses need to make decisions based on data all the time. One crucial part of analyzing data is the process of hypothesis testing. Without hypothesis and hypothesis tests, people risk drawing the wrong conclusions and making bad decisions. Administrators from all professions rely on the accuracy of hypothesis testing completed by skilled data scientists. In this tutorial you will be able to learn and accomplish the following:

  • Explore the theory of hypothesis testing and become familiar with terminologies associated with the process.
  • Step by step, learn the process of how to conduct a hypothesis test.
  • Apply hypothesis testing to a specific example.
  • Learn about decision rules in hypothesis testing.
  • Differentiate between different types of hypothesis tests.

What is Hypothesis Testing?¶

In terms of Data Science, hypothesis testing is a statistical method used to determine the validity of a hypothesis. It involves collecting, analyzing, and evaluating a sample of data to determine the probability of the null hypothesis being true or false. This means that data scientists verify the validity of a hypothesis statement based on sampled data. Contrary to one’s assumptions, data scientists want to disprove the null hypothesis, meaning the null hypothesis is false. A null hypothesis claims that the effect being studied does not exist. It can also be described as the hypothesis in which no relationship exists between two sets of data.

For example, a medical researcher may find that taking vitamin C daily does not affect the duration of a cold. Another example might be that Gender does not influence job satisfaction levels. These are two practical examples of a null hypothesis in everyday life.

In addition to null hypotheses, hypothesis testing includes alternative hypotheses. It is considered the “default” statement that is to be tested and thus rejected or supported by the data analysis.

Vocabulary used in Hypothesis Testing:¶

When learning about hypothesis testing, it is important to know and understand the following vocabulary terms:

  1. Null Hypothesis (H0):A null hypothesis in a statistical test (Denoted as H0 and read as “H-nought”) is the statement that there is no significant correlation between two specified populations, or any observed difference due to random chance.
  2. Alternative Hypothesis (H1 or HA): Alternate hypotheses (Denoted as H1 or HA) suggest that there is a significant relationship between two datasets. This represents a researcher’s prediction that they are trying to prove.

Note: H0 must always contain equality(=). HA always contains a difference(≠, >, <).

  1. One-tailed Test: We define H0 as an equality of two values. Our alternative hypothesis suggests that there is only ONE inequality (value A > value B but not value A < value B and vice versa).
  2. Two-tailed Test: Much like a one-tailed test, we define H0 as an equality of two values. However, our alternative hypothesis suggests that the two values are NOT equal. In other words, the alternative hypothesis cares about both inequalities (value A > value B AND value A < value B).
  3. Observed Difference: The difference between the values of two groups that is calculated in our observed sample
  4. P-value: The fraction of samples (assuming the null hypothesis is true) that are similar to our observed difference. It is denoted by the letter p.
  5. Significance Level: Often denoted by α (alpha), this represents the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis. Commonly used significance levels include 0.05, indicating a 5% significance.
  6. Type I Error: We reject the null Hypothesis when it is actually true.
  7. Type II Error: We fail to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false.

Step 2: State the null and alternative hypotheses.¶

As stated before, we need to identify a null and alternative hypothesis. An example of code stating these hypothesis can be shown as follows:

In [19]:
H0 = "There is no statistically significant difference in the number of aerial photos taken above shore than the number of aerial photos taken above water."
HA = "There is a statistically significant difference in the number of aerial photos taken above shore than the number of aerial photos taken above water.  Specifically, more aerial photographs are taken above shore than above water."

Our null hypothesis is that there is no statistically significant difference in the number of aerial photos taken onshore than the number of aerial photos taken offshore, while our alternative hypothesis states that there is a statistically significant difference in the number of aerial photos taken onshore than the number of aerial photos taken offshore. Specifically, more aerial photographs are taken onshore than offshore.

Step 3: Choose significance level¶

A significance level (sometimes denoted as α) determines the threshold for rejecting the null hypothesis. Commonly used significance levels are 0.05 (5%) and 0.01 (1%).

In [20]:
significance_level = 0.05 # Sets the significance level to 0.05 (5%)

Choose a statistical test based on the research question, type of data, and assumptions. Some examples might include: Comparison of means, correlation between two columns, and Chi-Squared Tests. Remember that my original hypothesis states that on average, there are more aerial photographs taken above land than above water. This means that I am comparing the means of two cases within the dataset. Because I am comparing two means, I have chosen to run the "comparison of means" test, as shown in the code below in the next step:

Step 5: Calculate observed difference/correlation between two means or variables¶

In a hypothesis test, we must find an observed difference/correlation before running permutations. While an observed difference can be negative, it wouldn’t make much sense, so we often calculate the difference between the larger value and smaller value (Larger minus Smaller).

In [21]:
# Create empty lists for photographs above land and water
photos_onshore = []

Step 6: Create a permutation function based on the type of hypothesis test¶

Depending on the type of hypothesis test, we need to create a function that simulates a random sample from the data. Since we are comparing two means, the code needed is as follows:

In [23]:
def simulate_two_groups(data1, data2):
    n = len(data1) #Get length of first group
    data = pd.concat([data1, data2]) #Get all data
    data = data.sample(frac=1) #Reshuffle all data
    group1 = data.iloc[:n] #Get random first group
    group2 = data.iloc[n:] #Get random second group
    return group1.mean() - group2.mean() #Calculate mean difference

After running this code for a set number of iterations, we can add them to a list and change said list to a pandas dataframe to make observations and analyses later on. This is accomplished in the code below:

The histogram represents the frequency of a specific difference in means based on the permutations. Since there is no data to the right of this dotted line, it solidifies my hypothesis that more photos are taken above shore than above water.

Step 10: Calculate p-value¶

The p-value determines the probability of each permutation being as extreme as, or more extreme than, the observed difference/correlation, assuming the null hypothesis is true. The p-value is compared to the significance level to make decisions about the null hypothesis. If the p-value is less than the significance level, the null hypothesis is rejected and we say that the difference/correlation is statistically significant. Otherwise, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and say that the difference/correlation is not statistically significant.

In [27]:
p_value=np.mean(permutations.permutations > permutations.observed_difference)
p_value
Out[27]:
0.0

Since the p-value is 0.0 (0%), it is less the alpha value of 0.05 (5%); thus. the difference is statistically significant. In other words, we reject the null hypothesis.

In [28]:
if p_value > significance_level:
    print(f"{p_value} > {significance_level}: We fail to reject the null hypothesis.  {H0}")
else:
    print(f"{p_value} < {significance_level}: We reject the null hypothesis.  {HA}")

0.0 < 0.05: We reject the null hypothesis.  There is a statistically significant difference in the number of aerial photos taken above shore than the number of aerial photos taken above water.  Specifically, more aerial photographs are taken above shore than above water.

Step 11: Check assumptions and validate results¶

As stated before, there is a lot data to work with, so this hypothesis test is reliable in determining if more photos are taken above shore than the amount of photos taken above water when estimating the population of harbor seals.

Step 12: Determine relevance to real-world applications (practical significance)¶

In the real world, we can assume that harbor seals spend more time offshore than onshore. In practical terms, scientists and biologists would need to focus more of their energies photographing and studying seals in the water if they are to gather more facts and information about this species.

Tutorial 2: Correlations: Visualization and Coefficients.¶

Introduction:¶

When considering data analysis, correlation analysis uses statistical techniques that help us determine relationships wiCalthin two or more variables within our data. Correlation analysis reveals interesting patterns and connections that impact decisions and predictions.

In this tutorial, we'll explore the following:

  • Explore the theory of correlation analysis and visualization and become familiar with terminologies associated with the process.
  • Step by step, learn the process of how to conduct correlation analysis and visualization
  • Learn how to calculate, interpret, and visualize correlation coefficients
  • Explore how to use correlation coefficients in data science.
  • NOTE: We will be using Python as our programming language.

What is Correlation Analysis and Visualization?¶

Correlation coefficients are numerical values that indicate how closely two variables are related. They range from -1 to 1 (inclusive), where -1 means a perfect negative relationship, 0 means there is no relationship between variables, and 1 means a perfect positive relationship. As the coefficient approaches 0, it becomes weaker, whereas if a correlation coefficient approaches -1 or 1, the stronger it becomes. A negative relationship means that as one variable increases, the other decreases, and vice versa, whereas a positive relationship means that as one variable increases, the other also increases, and vice versa.

In data science, the most common visualization technique for correlation analysis is a scatter plot, which visually displays the relationship between two numerical variables by plotting each data point on a 2D plane. The position of the points indicate the strength and direction of the correlation. For more complex analysis involving three or more numerical variables, a correlation matrix (also known as a heatmap) is often used to show the correlation coefficients between all pairs of variables in a dataset. Other visualization techniques for correlation analysis include bubble charts, line charts, and box plots. In the case of this tutorial, we will only be using scatter plots and heatmaps.

When to use Correlation Analysis and Visualization:¶

Correlation Analysis can be used for many different reasons. These include but are not limited to:

  • To identify patterns: Find trends and connections between variables in survey data
  • To test hypotheses: Determine if a relationship exists between two or more variables
  • To diagnose issues: Discover potential company issues
  • To test new measurement tools: Determine if a new instrument is reliable or valid
  • To explore non-causal relationships: Find out if there is an association between variables, but don't expect to find a causal relationship

In the world of data science, correlation analysis is used in areas of study. For example, physicians may use correlation analysis to determine the relationship between diet and a particular illness. Businesses may use this technique for market research, pricing strategies and sales forecasting. The US government uses correlation analysis for budget and tax purposes, crime and socioeconomic risk, and social spending. Lastly, correlation analysis is even used in education for curriculum and assessment design.

Vocabulary used in correlation analysis and visualization:¶

When learning about correlation analysis, it is important to know and understand the following vocabulary terms:

  1. Correlation: A statistical measurement that describes the relationship between two or more numerical variables.
  2. Correlation coefficient: A number (between -1 and 1) that indicates the strength and direction of a correlation.
  3. Positive correlation: When an independent variable increases by one unit, the dependent variable also increases.
  4. Negative correlation: When an independent variable increases by one unit, the dependent variable decreases.
  5. Bivariate: A type of correlation analysis that determines if a relationship exists between two variables.
  6. Multivariate: A type of correlation analysis that determines if a relationship exists between more than two variables.
  7. Pearson’s Correlation Coefficient: A coefficient that multiplies the deviations from the mean for two variables, and divides by the product of the standard deviation. It is useful for showing the strength of a correlation.
  8. Overplotting: Overlapping data points in a scatter plot.
  9. Heatmap: A matrix that shows the correlation coefficients between two variables. This is especially useful for multivariate correlation analysis.

Steps of correlation analysis and visualization:¶

Step 1: Collect Data.¶

The dataset I have chosen is the aerial photographs of Harbor Seal Locations In California between 2001 and 2003. The data can be found in this link: https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/harbor-seals-ds106-9df81

Step 2: Decide which variables to use¶

Since correlation analysis requires numerical values, not all data can be used as a variable. In this case, my choices are limited to only numerical data types (ints and floats). For the sake of this tutorial, I will be performing multivariate correlation analysis. This means I will be using more than two variables. For the hypothesis test tutorial, I wanted to see what the relationship was between the average number of seals located onshore and offshore. This meant that I needed to include location as a variable. However, when using correlation analysis, location is not considered a “numerical” data type.

There is a way around this predicament. Another way to determine the location of an object is to use its position in terms of the x and y positions of each photograph, which are both numerical values. The three variables that I will use in this tutorial are PHOTOCOUNT, X (x-position of photograph(s)), and Y (y-position of photograph(s)).

Step 3: Calculate the Correlation Coefficients¶

In order to calculate the correlation coefficients, one must use the Pearson's correlation coefficient. However, because Pearson’s correlation coefficient is the default in pandas, we don't have to do this as a separate step. The .corr() function will do this for us. We can easily determine the correlation coefficients between two variables. Keep in mind, since I am doing multivariate correlation analysis, I need to calculate three correlation coefficients. This can be accomplished using the following lines of code:

This code represents the correlation coefficient between each individual photograph and its x-value. In this case, the correlation coefficient is -0.066. As you can see, this is a weak negative correlation, meaning that as the number of photographs increases, the x-position of a photograph decreases. As one moves along the x-axis in the positive direction, the fewer aerial photographs of seals will be taken.

As one moves along the positive y-axis, more aerial photographs of seals will be taken.

In other words, as one moves along the positive x-axis, the y-position of a photograph decreases.

Step 4: Create and analyze scatter plot(s)¶

A scatter plot is type of mathematical visualization that uses dots to represent values for different numeric variables. The position of each dot on the horizontal and vertical axes indicates values for an individual data point. Scatter plots can be used to observe relationships between variables and can be created in altair using the .mark_point() method when creating a chart.

In order to visualize these correlations, we need to create a scatter plot, where the dependent variable is located on the y-axis and the independent variable(s) are located on the x-axis. Because I am using three variables, I need to show 3 scatter plots, one with PHOTOCOUNT on the x-axis and X (the x-position of a photograph) on the y-axis, one with PHOTOCOUNT on the x-axis and Y (the y-position of a photograph) on the y-axis, and one with X (the x-position of a photograph) on the x-axis and Y (the y-position of a photograph) on the y-axis. Python has many libraries to visualize correlations. However, this tutorial will only use one: Altair. For those who are unfamiliar with this, Altair refers to a Python library primarily used for creating data visualizations. The following code can be used to create a scatter plot for the PHOTOCOUNT and X (x-position) variables.

Step 5: Create and analyze Heatmap:¶

Sometimes, scatter plots have too many points condensed in one area, making it hard to analyze. This is what is known as “overplotting”. Thus, a heatmap (also known as a correlation coefficient matrix) is used to visualize all of the coefficients between two numeric variables. The heatmap allows analysts to determine the strength and direction of a correlation between 2 variables. The size of the heatmap is “n by n” where “n” represents the amount of numerical variables being analyzed. In this case, I have three variables, which means my heatmap will be 3x3 in size.

We can use Altair to also create a correlation coefficient matrix. This can be accomplished used the .mark_rect() function when creating a chart in altair. The heatmap for PHOTOCOUNT, X, and Y is created using the following code:

In [39]:
variables = ["X","Y","PHOTOCOUNT"] # Make sure that the heatmap only includes these 3 variables.
In [38]:
# Creates a DataFrame with the correlation coefficients between 2 of the three variables
seals_corr = seals[variables].corr(numeric_only=True).stack().reset_index().rename(columns={0:"corr","level_0":"var1","level_1":"var2"})

# Creates a heatmap where the PHOTOCOUNT, X, and Y variables are used.
base = alt.Chart(seals_corr, title="Seals Correlation Matrix").mark_rect().encode(
    x=alt.X("var1:N",title=None),
    y=alt.Y("var2:N",title=None),
    color=alt.Color("corr",title="Correlation coefficient").scale(scheme='blueorange')
).properties(width=300,height=300)

# Creates text on top of the s
text = base.mark_text(baseline='middle').encode(
    alt.Text('corr:Q',format=".2f"),
    color=alt.condition(
        (alt.datum.corr < -0.5) | (alt.datum.corr > 0.5),
        alt.value('white'),
        alt.value('black')
    )
)

base+text
Out[38]:

This heatmap represents the relationship among all three variables. Each square is given a color based on the correlation coefficent between 2 variables. Based on the heatmap, PHOTOCOUNT has the weakest correlation between X and/or Y as separate entities because the squares have very little color. This means that when considering location as a variable, using only one geographical spot in the x,y grid does not provide conclusive evidence. However, when comparing the X location to the Y location, the correlation coefficient drastically increases in strength. This means there is a strong (negative) correlation. This is most likely because the camera is following the seals as they swim through the ocean. Finally, the heatmap does not show any relationship between PHOTOCOUNT and the x,y location.

Step 6: Draw conclusions¶

In summary, the correlation coefficient describes how one variable moves in relation to another. A positive correlation coefficient indicates that as one variable increases, so does the other, with a value of 1 denoting a perfect positive correlation. A negative correlation coefficient indicates taht as one variable increases, the other one decreases, with a value of -1 showing a perfect negative (or inverse) correlation. A value of 0 means there is no correlation between two variables.

It is also important to remember that correlation coefficients measure the numerical relationship between two variables, but it does not imply causality. There may be a relationship between the two variables, but one does not necessarily cause the other. In terms of this tutorial, PHOTOCOUNT has a very weak correlation between both the X and Y locations as separate entities. However, when comparing X to Y directly, there is a correlation between the two. This correlation may not be helpful to scientists who are trying to determine the best locations to photograph harbor seals. Going forward, data scientists would need to choose different variables and approaches to determine the best locations to find harbor seals and therefore determine total population.

Step 7: Practical significance¶

As previously stated, the correlation between PHOTOCOUNT and X, Y was proven to be weak. Further testing would need to be done to help scientists find the best location for photographs.

Analyzing correlation coefficients is one step of data analysis. It can be used in the real world in many different situations, including finance (determining the correlation between different stock prices and companies), healthcare (determining the correlation between diet and exercise with blood pressure), education (determining the correlation between study hours and test scores), and many more. Depending on the type of data, you need to select the appropriate correlation coefficients using pearson's correlation coefficients. One word of warning: when interpreting correlation coefficients, be aware that other factors may influence the relationship between your variables.
